description.text:
This is a very expandable system ... it can be multiple channels on a rotating drum with multiple drums with gearing between the vertical and horizontal systems you can add more and more to create a very large array of percussive triggers ... I\'m still tweaking the various different multiple systems.  
Yes every part here is designed to be makde with a CupCake MakerBotable ... except for the rubber band ... get one from your local post office!  
I wish I had a MakerBot to actually build and test my creations!  
This is another of many entries to the makezine.com/go/makerbot  contest ...
blog.makezine.com/archive/2010/04/makerbot_giveaway.html

See the bill of materials for quantities of each to MakerBot for the 1-Channel PPRM ... then MakerBot the parts and start fitting them together into your new drumming/tapping machine as shown in the diagrams.  
A rubber band is the spring around the horizontal extensions out to the hammer pulls the hammer back to a stand-up position.  
Program the drum set by sticking the programming pegs into the holes on the drum ... 
Set different objects in front of the hammer and crank the machine to hear the rhythm you created ... 
It\'s a learning process to understand beats/measure ... then with 2:1 gearing and a 2nd machine you can increase the resolution to 32 beats/measure.  
BTW, if you store a few extra programming pins inside the drum you now have a second noise source ... albeit not percussive but more like a rattle. 
If you successfully make this with a 3D printer please send me the build-file and machine type so it can be uploaded here for others to use.

This is my rendering of a modular rocket.  The fins can be installed any of a number of ways (swept back, forward, out and of course, plain old straight like you see in the photo).  The tube with the launch lug has a coupler that separates, and is meant to mount (with glue) to the base of the nosecone.  The bottom tube fits a B or C engine perfectly.  You will need to drill a small hole for your desired shock cord and another in the cone's coupler.  A streamer fits in the smaller top tube and a chute (tightly) in the larger one.  If you want it to be longer, break out one of the tubes and print it multiple times along with the second coupler and just stack them.  I will post individual pieces soon too.  This rocket is a kit for the NoVa Mini Maker Faire in March.  I will shortly make these kits available, built or unbuilt.  Contact me over eMail if you want one.  I will shortly be posting rafts for mass production ahead of the Faire.

Print all parts for a single size rocket, print the couplers and additional tubes and just stack them up.  Remember that your rocket should not be too long (about 16") because you will be pushing the C engine weight limit.

My biggest reason for doing this is noise. The built in PSU is loud. Compared to that, most computer power supplies are practically silent. I have tons of older ATX power supplies kicking around anyways.

As an added bonus, the power supply can provide power for a raspberry pi running octoprint, 5 or 12v lighting strips, and any other little accessories you need.

This assumes you have already added a relay for the heated bed. If you haven't, do that first!

• ATX power supply (I used 600W). Make sure the 5vSB can handle 2 amps.
  • 24 pin extension cable like StarTech ATX24POWEXT
  • 4 pin CPU power extension cable like StarTech ATXP4EXT
  • 2 chassis mount 2.1mm power jacks with 13mm mounting holes (ones I have are Mode Electronics 31-134-2)
  • 80mm case fan - I recommend Noctura because they are really quiet
  • Optional - If you want octopi to be able to turn the power supply on and off, you'll need an NPN transistor and a 1k resistor

• Cut the male end of the extension cables off, leaving as much wire as possible attached to the female ends
  • Google "ATX pinout" to determine which wire does what. Remember most show the male plug, and you are working with the female side, so you may have to mirror it. The colors below may differ if your extension cable doesn't follow the usual color scheme, so double check!
  • Wire one of the ground wires and one of the 5v wires (usually red) to the first power jack
  • Wire one of the ground wires and the 5v SB wire (usually purple) to the second power jack
  • Wire the CPU extension cable wires to the power in on your relay board. Yellow is positive.
  • Wire 12v (usually yellow) and ground to the power input on the mainboard
  • Wire 12v and ground to the fan in the backplate

If you are going to have octopi control the power supply, follow this guide for how to wire the transistor: http://www.instructables.com/id/Using-the-Raspberry-Pi-to-control-an-ATX-power-sup/ - The base is connected to the GPIO pin on the Raspberry Pi in series with a 1k resistor. The collector is connected to PS_ON (green), and the emitter is connected to ground on the ATX (any black wire).

If you are not using the pi to control it, connect the PSON and one of the ground wires to a momentary switch to turn the power supply on. If you want to modify the backplate to accomodate your switch, I've included the fusion 360 design file.

• Make or obtain a 2.1mm power jack to micro usb cable. Plug it into the 5vSB connector and the raspberry pi. Now your pi will be powered at all times, even when the power supply is "off".
  • The other 5v connector is switched with the power supply, and can be used for 5v LED lighting.
  • Plug the power supply into the backplate just like a computer power supply
  • Connect the GPIO wire to the pi and use https://github.com/kantlivelong/OctoPrint-PSUControl plugin to control it

title: lg 23et83v-w Touchscreen monitor VESA adapter plate

description.text: Needed to make an adapter plate to mount my LG Touchscreen onto my VESA wall mount. It's been holding well for a couple of weeks now.

Printed at 70% infill. Use threadlocker when assembling.  
Important note - Make sure your mount has space for the M4 bolts needed to attach the two pieces. If not,  you'll need to either make countersunk holes for the bolt heads or print as a single unit.  
Needs a 6 inch #8 rod (or M4) and two associated locknuts (or nut and lock washer combo) through the main area to connect to the monitor. Connect plate to adapter so that the lip of the adapter faces down, and join it using M4 bolts (two 20mm and two 16mm),nuts, and lock washers. The VESA holes use M5 bolts (4 20 or 16mm) and again, nuts and lock washers. Avoid over-tightening as you may cause snaps in the plastic (I had minor separation but it's still solid).  
the threaded rod needs to be pretty tight to "stick" when you tilt the monitor, but the monitor still seems to droop a bit after a few days. I may update the design to counteract that, as I had meant to when I made it.  
I cut down a USB B (printer) cable to fit my oversized VideoSecu Vesa mount, but I would recommend getting a 90 degree cable instead.

title: Runcam Split Camera Mount for Martian II or Alien Frame

description.text:
This is a variation of Mhodder camera mount. It's intended to soft-mount the camera on the side plates by addind a TPU mount on it.

You should print the side plates using a ridig material like PLA or ABS, and the camera mounts with soft material like TPU.

Then you must join both parts together with Epoxy or CA glue.

You'll need 6 M2x6 screws to fix the camera.
You'll be able to adjust camera angle from -5º to 45º.

The Sideplates are equal on both sides, but the TPU mounts have left and right versions.

You can choose between two sideplate designs: One light and one heavy. The heavy one is intended to offer more support for the top plate during crashes and to help reduce vibrations on camera. With 50% infill on PLA, the heavy version should weight about 5g each side.

Note: It also will work for:

  • Runcam Swift Mini
  • Runcam Split V2
  • Caddx Turbo S1

This is a piece to retain a common size of earpiece plugs to the top of the Icom IC-T70 radio.

I've tested it with a number of third party 2-pin Icom handsets, monophones, earpieces etc. and they all seem to be roughly the same so there's a good chance it will fit yours too!

A 1.5mm slot is cut in the side to let you slip the wire through, and up to 13 mm wide antenna bases can be used without interference.

When mounted it retains the plug body, preventing accidental removal since you have to remove the antenna first.

Update: 2017-10-14: I noticed the FA-S270C antenna has the center pin quite far away from the edge, the original part is tall enough that this antenna won't work.

I've uploaded a _Short variant that in theory sits 1mm closer to the radio, but you may still need to use a file/dremel to get everything right if you want to use the original antenna.
The original part works well with all my Diamond/Nagoya/Comet third part antennas (I tested the SRH-536, Comet SMA-24 (my favourite), and the Comet SMA-209 stubby).

The typical SMA antenna has the center pin less than 1 mm from the bottom, while the Icom antenna center is around 2.7 mm from the bottom.

I printed mine with no raft and tree-like support with the base of the part 1mm above the table.

Added detail drawing in case someone else needs the measurements.

The Vectrex arcade machine is still one of the best ever made. It is also the only home arcade machine that used a vector display and therefore can not be experienced in an emulator to its entirety. It was launched in 1982 right before the video game crash of 83, and was largely a commercial failure unfortunately. That did not stop it from getting some great games and becoming a cult classic. Great new home brew games are still being made to this day along with other hardware upgrades. This was all possible because the original designers released all the information about the system after it was discontinued, way before anyone was open sourcing anything. In that spirit, I am releasing my replacement controller design!
I have been making and selling them for a year + now and feel it is time to share the design with the world!

Vectrex4ever!

Thank you for everyone that bought one.
I will keep selling them for $100 for those that do not want to or can not make them. It takes a good deal of time to assemble them, so I don't make much profit per hour, it is a labor of love. I also include a nice box and extra parts. I can print them in any color.

-Fully compatible with original, overlays fit and it fits on the front of the Vectrex!
-Designed for analog joysticks
-Works with high quality buttons! Major upgrade! If you want the Sanwa, they fit nice with overlays, but if your not using an overlay on the controller you can go with the bigger 20mm ones. I like the smaller 18mm Sanwa best so far.

description.text:
Handle Upgrade for a Gent's Saw style dovetail saw.

I got the idea from this guys youtube video:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uz_jni42FZ0

But thought it would be fun to try modeling it with Fusion360.

The basic pattern I followed can be found here:
http://www.blackburntools.com/articles/saw-handle-templates/index.html
(I used the 9-inch open pattern)

Usually this kind handle of is made from one piece of wood and the saw blade itself is used to cut a slot in the middle. I chose to make a left and right side for easy, no supports printing. The thin (.4 mm) spacer goes between them to compensate for the blade thickness.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

.2

Infill:

20%

Notes:

I printed my prototype with PETg, Slicer was Slic3r - Prusa Edition and the "cubic infill" setting. Even with that low infill setting, it seemed strong enough. I believe most of the strength comes from the walls.

The left size needs to be flipped over so it prints flat side down. The screw holes are meant to be blind (not all the way through) but diameter is small enough so no supports are needed. There is a slight overhang where the saw blade rib goes, but I've included a small ridge so you don't need to hope your slicer does the right thing here and can be easily scraped away in post processing. Just use bridge mode setting and it should be fine.

Since there is some gluing involved, I set the bottom layer count to 0 so the infill pattern would be exposed in the hope that what might give better glue adhesion. With the small infill setting the pattern still showed some scaring with 3 top layers. Next time I'll use 4 top layers.

Assembly

I started by gluing the spacer to one side with epoxy. Then marked the saw blade with the template and removed the excess material and drilled the mounting holes. The two sides then sandwich the saw blade and are fastened with 4 #10-24 x 3/4" machine screws. I had to drill out the left side slightly because of printer spooge, but left the other side snug so the screws would self tap.

it uses metal drawer sliders for linear rails, and threaded rod + stepper motors for moment.

it was all built for around 300$ USD.
tools needed to make this include basic woodworking tools (if you decide to make some parts out of wood) and a laser for cutting the cardboard. you can print out the .dxf files and cut them out by hand, but it works much better with a laser. Also for the wooden parts, having a CNC machine available makes this a lot easier, since i built this in a college Fabrication Lab, i had some tools available to me that you may not. printing the files out on paper, and then gluing that to the wood for a cut out template also works if you want to use hand tools

The parts are all separate and the straps are all lengthened, so cutting and gluing is required but it should fit a range of heads. I also included screw caps so that the details of the movie costume can be accurately represented.

Also look for my Mad Max Fury Road Leg Brace files.

Painting/Finishing was done after assembly, in this order:
Sand
Auto Primer
Black Gloss
Silver
Black/Brown Acrylic washes for pop and weathering
Egg Shell Sealer
Rust and Blood details
Egg Shell Sealer

Then I lined the inside of the mask with foam to make it comfortable and added a plastic chain from the hardware store that I painted and weathered the same way as the mask

title: Fast printing filament spool roller using 608 bearings. Designed with M3D in mind.

description.text: A really quick printing filament spool holder/roller inspired by a similar design called TUSH. I've heard good things about it but it didn't fit on my M3D's print bed. So i designed a different one, which not only fits on my printer's bed, but also only takes about 40 mins per piece. You will need to print out 4 of them, test fit the bearings, and then heat the stubs with a lighter until they start melting and just push the stubs through the bearings so they meet in the middle. Keep applying pressure for about 30 seconds and... voila! You have a spool roller. Just be careful not to burn yourself during assembly. I highly recommend some sort of anti-slip mat to put it onto.

description.text:
After printing and using 3Dworkshop's vibration dampers (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2557700) for a while, I realised that the PLA I used was so stiff that it wasn't really doing anything much. Hence I decided to design my own vibration damper that is meant to be printed in flexible PLA.

I have included two versions with different thickness (to provide different level of stiffness/damping depending on how flexible is your PLA). The one depicted in the pics was the 1.1mm version. It is printed using Hobby King's flexible PLA (which is still kind of stiff, compared to, say, Ninjaflex).

Other flexible materials such as TPU might work, though I have never tried them.

You may need to play around with the extrusion width (I used 0.52 in Slic3r) to control the number of walls for each of the layers. Note that the stiffness is probably also affected by your choice of extrusion width (which determines whether there would be gaps between the inner and outer walls). I deliberately left some gaps between the walls in some of the layers to ensure that there is still some bounce in the final print. In Cura, you can force this behaviour by turning off filling of the gaps.

I designed the basic shape in Onshape and played around with the thickness and printed a few samples until I get the bounce and flexibility that I'm happy with.

The video shows the amount of play left in my current print (the 1.1mm version) .

title: Verticle Mount Feet for Mean Well SE-450-24 (and other similar p/s with the same hole pattern)

description.text:
UPDATED: new files for more even leg length, added indicator for longer side screw distance (triangle).

(see cover for Se-450-24: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2556126)
I replaced my stock Taz power supply with a Mean Well SE-450-24.
The venting side of the power supply has large holes that would be easy for small screws or whatever to enter through, so I like to turn the power supply vertically and the fan pointing away from my printer bed (to avoid the added draft with ABS). To make it more stable when standing vertically, I added a stabilizing stand/feet.
There are two different designs required; one to miss the end cover and one for the opposite side. The ones shown here are done in PLA to match the cover. You will need four M4X16mm long cap screw and washers (available at HomeDepot), I did not want to drive 12 miles to HD and had some hex head M4x16mm screws and just used a hacksaw to make a slot in the head so I could use a flat blade screw driver. The M4 washers I used are about .5mm thick and less than 5.5mm in outside diameter.
This design should work for most power supplies that are 50mm tall and have four inserts on the side that are 25mm apart. Note that the insert closest to the side with no vent holes should be 13.3mm to the side, whereas the one on top is 12.3 mm to the vented side. If you have trouble getting the screws started try flipping the stands 180 degrees, or measure first to determine which insert is farther from the edge. NOTE: THE SIDE WITH THE LONGER SCREW DISTANCE HAS A TRIANGLE ON THE FOOT.
I added some small strips of rubber drawer liner which reduces the noise a bit and adds friction so it will not slide. Just used Elmer's High Strength glue stick to attach the liner pieces.

title: Replicator 2X Extruder Base/Adaptor for Flexible Filaments

description.text:
Update: Version 2 uploaded 28/02/2014. Have made some minor adjustments to the margins to improve fit, added a small support tab to the front of the thing to support that corner, and mirror-imaged the thing for the left extruder.  
May produce a third version with the outer margin opened to allow for a view of the drive gear at some point.  
Both ABS and NinjaFlex loading/unloading/printing have been smooth for the past 48 hours of operation.

This thing has been remixed from the design by rmcniff: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:222667 to work with the 3in1 Universal Extruder upgrade by DHeadrick: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:136423 After acquiring some NinjaFlex filament I ran into some of the same filament feed problems that have been discussed in the MakerBot Operators Google Group (https://groups.google.com/forum/#!searchin/makerbot/ninjaflex/makerbot/KUwEIXMlVtk/Mcze9mt0hskJ). While my 3in1 Replicator 2X aluminium extruder upgrade does exactly as advertised (they rock!), the filament has enough flexibility to buckle during loading/printing. As I didn't want to have to swap my 3in1 drive block out for another design with a filament guide below the drive gear, I have modified the base of the rmcniff extruder to interface with the 3in1 universal upgrade (using Geomagic Studio to subtract components, combined with some hand editing). I have successfully printed in NinjaFlex and ABS since installing the printed part. Thus far, both filament types feed smoothly and I have yet to experience air prints using the NinjaFlex filament. I will post more photos of the part soon and will also likely make some minor modifications to the design.

Sliced in MakerWare and printed in ABS with: 25% infill
3 shells
0.15mm with supports. You may want to ream the filament guide hole to ensure smooth filament passage.

description.text: This is my first Parametric object (in fact the first think I've done with OpenScad), and also my first entry into Thingiverse, so don't be too hard on me :p This is a parametric Drawer Set. In front of the drawers you can put a customizable piece or cover (that is glued to the rest of the drawer) and where you can put your logo or anything you fancy. This also serves as the drawer's handle. The files CoverCajon (yes I'm spanish) are examples made with SolidEdge for this piece with several designs, from the Apple logo, to the RepRap Logo. Update 29 Jun: I've made an update, for the precission of the rounded corners and all circle-shaped holes. I wasn't very pleased with the result so I added a new parameter to specify the number of sides (precission) of this shapes.

• Download the files config.scad, drawer.scad, drawerBox.scad, cover.scad & separator.scad.

  • Config the config.scad file with your preferences:
    2.1 Single Drawer Parameters:
    -SingleDrawerWidth: width of the drawer (that is if you look at it from where the cover with the logo is)
    -SingleDrawerHeight: height of the drawer (same point of view as before).
    -SingleDrawerDepth: how far is the drawer to extend inside the drawer box.
    -SingleDrawerThickness: the thickness of the walls in the drawer.
    -SingleDrawerRoundness: the border radius of the drawer.
    -SingleDrawerHandleDepth: How much the handle (where the cover is glued on) sticks out of the box).
    -SingleDrawerHandleMargin: The height of the margin on wich the cover lays.
    2.2 Single Drawer dividers: this are the marks where the separator can fit.
    -SingleDrawerSeparateIn2: divide the box in 2.
    -SingleDrawerSeparateIn3: divide the box in 3 (is compatible with the previous one).
    -SingleDrawerSeparateIn4: divide the box in 4 (I think it leaves small parts, but you may find it use).
    2.3 Guides: This help the drawer stay in it's place and just slide in the box:
    -SingleDrawerHasGuides: Make the drawer (and the box) have guides.
    Note: the guides are the heigth of the SingleDrawerThickness parameter and stick out of the sides of the drawer half teh value of SingleDrawerThickness.
    2.4 Drawer Box Parameters (parameters for the box):
    -DrawerBoxThickness: the thickness of the walls of the box (it should be greater than the thickness of the single drawer).
    -DrawerBoxXDrawers: how many drawers lay horizontally.
    -DrawerBoxYDrawers: how many drawers lay vertically.
    -DrawerBoxHoleRatio: this is how big the spaces for the drawers are compared to the dimensions of the actual hole. It should be a tiny bit more than 1.
    -DrawerBoxRoundness: this is the border radius of the drawer box.
    2.5 Separator Parameters:
    -SeparatorThickness: This is used mainly to tell the SingleDrawer how much space to leave between Separator marks. Also determines the thickness of the separator, obvioulsly.
    -SeparatorHeightRatio: This is the ratio SeparatorHeight/(SingleDrawerHeight-SingleDrawerThickness), it should be less than 1.
    2.6 Cylinder Precission:
    -CirclePrecision: sets the number of sides a cylinder would have. The more sides the more cylinder like it will be but the bigger the stl and the more lines the printer has to print. If set to 0, OpenScad will automatically set a value (usually very low 5-8 depending on the size of the curve).

  • Print the drawerBox.scad render (that will hold the drawers).

  • Print as many drawer.scad renders as you need to fill the holes.

  • Print as many covers.scad renders as you need. You may also print anyone of the ones I made with various designs. Some tips if you wan't tomake your own: If you can make the drawer have a hole big enough to put your finger though it, it will make it easier to pull out (for example, the apple Logo, or the RepRapLogo do this).

  • Once you have the drawers and the covers, glue the covers to the drawers.

  • Print Separators to suit your needs. You may remove the RepRapLogo if you are holding smal pieces, as they could pass through the holes, or change the design to anything you like.
    • Enjoy!

description.text:
Why should a mailbox be boring? With this product, puzzle pieces can be removed and decorated with ease and infinite possibilities. Family households can let the kids paint or color pieces while other users could order monogrammed or labeled pieces. Holidays, seasons, favorite sports teams, and even garage sale signs can be implemented onto the mailbox's exterior.

Instead of a flag to signal outgoing mail, one of the front pieces can be painted or marked to signal when there is outgoing mail.

If you're interested in any of my other projects, check out my website!
https://www.tessa-wheeler.com/

Tips

-When cutting this mailbox, keep in mind some angles are not 90 degrees. Therefore, there might be some open space which requires additional attention.
-Wood glue is advised. I also glued the outer "net" sides to the inner "plain" sides before assembling the full mailbox. Experiment with this method as some layers might overlap at the edges.
-Consider gluing a tab(s) on the inside of the mailbox so the door does not fall in. I ended up not needed the tabs because my mailbox edges were flush.
-Play around with how the mailbox might be mounted and add nail holes where needed.

Universal rear-view mirror radar detector mount.  I once paid $80+ for a radar detector mount for my truck...  Never again! Now that I own a 3D printer.  This is the 2nd requested mod by my wife for her new (used) car.

This is in response to custom radar detector mounts costing so much, like: http://www.blendmount.com Instructions: -Print "RadarDetectorMount.stl"
-Insert an M8 X 1.25mm x 45mm head cap screw into the lower mirror mount
-Spin on a M8 x 1.25mm nylon locking nut and tighten it against the lower mirror mount on the 45mm long head cap screw
-Spin on a 2nd M8 x 1.25 mm nylon locking nut ~15mm up the 45mm long head cap screw
-Slide the printed detector mount on to the 45mm long head cap screw and secure with a 3rd nylon locking nut
-Tighten the 2 nylon locking nuts against the printed detector mount
-Take your detectors factory suction cup mount and pop out the suction cups
-Fasten the factory suction cup mount to the printed detector mount with two M6 x 1.0mm x 20mm head cap screws and 2 M6x 1.0mm nylon locking nuts
-Place the printed top mirror mount on top of the rear-view mirrors windshield bar
-Match the printed lower mirror mount to the top mirror mount and install two M8 x 1.25 x 25mm head cap screws in the two mount holes
-Tighten two M8 x 1.25mm nylon locking nuts to the screws exposed on the mirror mount
-Slide your radar detector onto the factory suction cup rail mount and begin making adjustments
-After desired position is acquired (may need to adjust the 45mm screw and its 2 nuts depending on your setup) tighten up your mirror mount, insert power and go for a test ride! It is pretty sturdy, almost too sturdy... I may revise the design after a while in the field. The wife said she would detail me on its performance and ride quality :) This "unique" mount fits right in with her "unique" MKT. I have only heard positive comments on the current setup, hmm, you know, she may just be sparing my feelings by not telling me it is hideous. Oh well, beta's and 1st runs aren't always "pretty" right? This was designed to easily print on a Thing-O-Matic; I would recommend 20% infill or greater for durability over the years. For reference this was a "perfect" fit for a 2010 Lincoln MKT running a Passport Escort 8500 X50. Make On! Uploaded source Sketchup file for your modding pleasures

I designed this for the Mars 58-v2 parachute system .
I have gave space on the plate for the parachute , mayday system and a small lightweight battery .

this is a project in progress will post more as i have it .

https://www.marsparachutes.com/product/mars-58-v2/

Screws needed :
4 m3 x 20
2 m3 x 12
6 m3 lock nuts

i done the plate in 2mm thick carbon fiber but you could easily use 3mm or if 3d printing, print solid and use as fine a layer as your printer will print to make it strong .
3d printing the plate may not be strong enough even at 3mm . if 3d printing with FDM printer you will want to see the post printing instructions bellow .

print clamps solid .

the design is so you can remove the thumb screws and still fold up the typhoon H for storage .

also this design will benefit from the new kickstarter project at :
https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/2123788781/mars-nova-drone-parachute-radio
very useful to deploy parachute .

also provided is the fusion 360 files
as well as step files .

the Bolt pattern for the system can be found here .
https://www.marsparachutes.com/wp-content/uploads/2016/01/58-BASE-Bolt-Pattern-1.pdf

NOTE : the 2 slots on the plate close to the end are there for people that 3d print
so that you can run a zip tie through the holes and around the arm of the drone .
this is done as a safety in case the 3d print separates you will not lose your parachute from the drone .

more to come .

title: Garden hose attachment to clean (drain) pipes from the inside.

description.text:
Drain pipes sometimes get clogged. There are off course several options to solve this (the best of which is to pay someone else to do it), but this is an easy way to try to solve the problem yourself.

This solution will not work if the clog is too far from your point of entry, if your region has a low water pressure or if the clog is very rigid.

So, this is how it works:

  1. Print according to the instructions below.
  2. Make the sphere nice and smooth.
  3. Drill 1mm holes in the sphere. Drill holes in the front (for the actrual cleaning) and on the back around the connection (for propulsion). Usually 8 holes for propulsion and 1 for cleaning works best.
  4. Connect to a half inch garden hose with hose clamps.
  5. Give it a quick test. The hose should start dancing with a little pressure (if you don't know what I mean, try it).
  6. Feed into the clogged drain pipe.
  7. Only turn on after the head is in the pipe.
  8. Feed the hose in after the head, play with the hose and hope for the best.
  9. Clean up and take a nice long shower. You've deserved it.

Strength is of the essence with this object. Think about high print temperature, low layer heights, strong materials, lots of perimeters and as much infill as you dare. I used Colorfabb nGen, 0.200 layer height, 5 perimeters, 75% infill and 235 degrees Celsius. Plenty of strength in that.

A second problem is bed adhesion due to the small surface area. I used a huge raft and lots of support to the build plate. Works for me but your results may vary.
